Project: Analyzing Marketing Campaigns¶

Introduction:¶

this a marketing dataset based on the data of an online subscription business.

the question(s) that posed that I am trying to know :

  • "How did this campaign perform?"

  • "Which channel is referring the most subscribers

  • "Why is a particular channel underperforming?"

Evaluating how a marketing campaign performed by:¶

  • Conversion Rate Matric to determine how effective a marketing team was at gaining new customers.
  • Retention Rate Matric to determine the number of remaining subscribers from the users who converted to the product.

1- Conversion Rate Matric¶

In [11]:
# Calculate the number of people we marketed to
total = marketing['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the number of people who subscribed
subscribers = marketing[marketing['converted']== True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the conversion rate
conversion_rate = subscribers/total
print('number of people we marketed to:',total,
      '\number of people who subscribed:',subscribers)
print(round(conversion_rate*100, 2), "%")

number of people we marketed to: 7309 
umber of people who subscribed: 1015
13.89 %

2- Retention Rate Matric¶

In [12]:
# Calculate the number of subscribers
total_subscribers = marketing[marketing['converted']== True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the number of people who remained subscribed
retained = marketing[marketing['is_retained']== True]['user_id'].nunique()

# Calculate the retention rate
retention_rate = retained/ total_subscribers
print(round(retention_rate*100, 2), "%")

In [13]:
# build a function to calculate conversion rate across any sub-segment I want.
def conversion_rate(dataframe, column_names):
    """ this function takes a DataFrame 
    and list of column names and outputs 
    the conversion rate across the column(s)
    """
    
   # Total number of converted users
    column_conv = dataframe[dataframe['converted']== True].groupby(column_names)['user_id'].nunique()

    # Total number users
    column_total = dataframe.groupby(column_names)['user_id'].nunique()
    
    # Conversion rate 
    conversion_rate = column_conv/column_total
    
    # Fill missing values with 0
    conversion_rate = conversion_rate.fillna(0)
    return conversion_rate

In [21]:
# create plot funcation to generate plots for sub-segments of the dataset
def plotting_conv(dataframe):
    """generate plots for sub-segments of the dataset"""
    for column in dataframe:
        # Plot column by dataframe's index
        plt.plot(dataframe.index, dataframe[column])
        plt.title('Daily ' + str(column) + ' conversion rate\n', 
                  size = 16)
        plt.ylabel('Conversion rate', size = 14)
        plt.xlabel('Date', size = 14)
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        # Show plot
        plt.show()  
        plt.clf()

expected_subs = converted['expected_spanish_conv'].sum() + converted['expected_arabic_conv'].sum() + converted['expected_german_conv'].sum()

# Calculate how many subscribers we actually got
actual_subs = converted[('converted','Spanish')].sum() + converted[('converted','Arabic')].sum() + converted[('converted','German')].sum()

# Subtract how many subscribers we got despite the bug
lost_subs = expected_subs - actual_subs
print(lost_subs)

32.144143192488265

32 subscribers may not seem like many, but for a small company this can be vitally important, especially when expanding to new markets.

The email portion of this campaign was actually run as an A/B test. Half the emails sent out were generic upsells to your product while the other half contained personalized messaging around the users’ usage of the site.¶

so I am going to look at the conversion rate for the control and personalization. Since we chose conversion rate as our key metrics for this test, so I'll evaluate whether or not conversion was higher in the personalization treatment compared with the control.

Comparing conversion rates¶

In [34]:
# checking the conversion rate for the control and personalization to evaluate whether or

Control conversion rate: 0.2814814814814815
Personalization conversion rate: 0.3908450704225352

as we can see that personalization converted users at a higher rate than the control. So, I will build a lift function to quantify by how much.

Creating lift funcation by calculating the difference between the treatment effect (or the mean) of the treatment compared to the treatment effect of the control divided by the treatment effect of the control.¶

In [35]:
# create a lift function to automate the process of calculating lift. 
def lift(a,b):
    # Calcuate the mean of a and b
    control_mean = np.mean(control)
    personalization_mean = np.mean(personalization)
    
    # Calculate the lift using a_mean and b_mean
    lift = (personalization_mean-control_mean)/control_mean
  
    return str(round(lift*100, 2)) + '%'
  
# Print lift() with control and personalization as inputs
print(lift(control, personalization))

38.85%

there's a large lift, which is mean the personalization variant outperformed the control¶

so I will determine whether the result is statistically significant using T-test. to understanding whether a test showed a positive result by chance or if it is reflective of a true difference between the variants

In [36]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
t = ttest_ind(control,personalization)
t
Out[36]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-2.7343299447505074, pvalue=0.006451487844694175)

p = 0.006. less than 0.05 so The personalization results are highly statistically significant.

Building an A/B test segmenting function¶

I will build funcation to segment data to check how new features are affecting specific demographics. Sometimes features that are highly appealing to one group are less appealing to others

In [37]:
def ab_segmentation(segment):
    """this funcation analyzes the impact of A/B tests 
    on segments of data that can reuse each time I
    want to conduct this kind of analysis.
    """
    # Build a for loop for each subsegment in marketing
    for subsegment in np.unique(marketing[segment].values):
        print(subsegment)
      
      # Limit marketing to email and subsegment
        email = marketing[(marketing['marketing_channel'] == 'Email') & (marketing[segment] == subsegment)]

        subscribers = email.groupby(['user_id', 'variant'])['converted'].max()
        subscribers = pd.DataFrame(subscribers.unstack(level=1)) 
        control = subscribers['control'].dropna()
        personalization = subscribers['personalization'].dropna()

        print('lift:', lift(control, personalization)) 
        print('t-statistic:', ttest_ind(control,personalization), '\n\n')

Often a treatment will not affect all people uniformly. So, I will run through two segments in our data that may be relevant to assessing the impact of our test.

  • 1st group 'language_displayed'
  • 2nd group 'age group'.
